{"/service/ndnp/tu/batch_tu_anita_ver01/data/sn85038531/00415621255/1920082501/1316.xml":{"full_text":"at\n1\n1J\nFOREIGN TRADE\nON DECLINE\nExporters Need to Amend\nMethods and Become More\nThan Mere Amateurs.\nCURTAIL EXTRAVAGANCES\n(The first Installment of an Important\nInterview with Frank A. Vanderllp,\neminent financier .and political authority\non worm political economy. Mr, van-\ntlerllD was seen at Ma beautiful home\n\"BeeehwOod.\" Soaraborough. overlook\ning tha Hudson river, liv Floyd Mac\nGriff, correspondent of the International\nNews Service. Tomorrow The News will\neuhllah tha second rhnnter or ihi in\ntervlew In which Mr. Vanderllp hrll-\nllantlv dlscnsse the world-wide iuu\ndan prohlem.)\nIBVVlOVD MACORIFF.I\nNew York. Auk. 2o.-Inherently, the\nAmerican business outlook Is sound\nbut the next six years cannot be o\nbounteously prosperous aft ilia past six\nyears, which were Inflated owing- to mi\nusual war conditions and unless the\npeople curtail luxurious extravagances\nthere will be aitnouitic anona.\nThat summarises, In a paragraph, the\nviews of Frank A. Vanderllp, one of tne\nforemost financiers In America, who dla\ncussed for tho Internatlonnl News Ser\nvice the business outlook of this nation\nfrom a broad standpoint.\nThere is little prospect.\" he said,\nof America retaining its present volume\nof foreign trade unless American ex\nporters, as a class, become more than\namateurs and change their methods.\n\"I do not aee how this country can\nenjoy as groat prosperity during; the\nnext six yenrs as In the past. I aee no\nevidence as to why there can be such\ncontinuance.\n\"The sooner this nation realties that\nnd gets back to the hard facts of eco\nnomic life and to a sounder business\nmorality, the better It will be.\n\"Artificial conditions, the oittrrrowth\nOf the war. which have been making our\nnational life so extravagant, must be\ncurtailed.\nI \"I do not mean by this that the work-\n,lng man Is not entitled to fair pay for\nan honest day's work. Nor do I mean\nwage Increases have not been beneficial.\nI think one may safely figure wages and\nother expenditures on a basis of two and\nK half times those of 1914. Where a dol\nJar was spent then. It now Is necessary\nI find In my own affairs, to spend 12.8(1.\n\"But the point Is that we should start\nnot necessarily or by any means with\nWages to reduce expenditures.\n\"Every one seems agreed that such a\nmove bo made but he is waiting for the\n'other fellow\" to make It. Cutting down\nthe hlnh cost of living is all very well,\nthe average person agrees, except when\nsuch cutting Interferes with his own\nprofits.\n\"Not only In our. business life, but\nIn our private affairs, I believe we all\nshould strive to be more frugal.\n\"Is the American business outlook to\nday Inherently sound?\" He was asked.\n\"Duslness In this country.\" Mr. Vnn\nderllp explained, \"Is largely dependent\nupon crops, There will be bounteous\ncrops thts year, especially of those\nharvested In the latter part \"bf the sea\nson.\n\"Bumper crops- tend to protect the\nUnited States from usual depression In\nthe home market.\"\n\"How about foreign trade He was\nasked.\n\"Our foreign trade gradually Is de\nclining, as figures Ustied monthly show,\nWith the exception of a few American\nIndustries with their own distributing\norganization abroad such as the Singer\n(tewing Machine company, the Reming\nton Typewriter company, the Standard\nOil company and the McCormlrk Har\nvesting Machinery people, we are ama\nteurs as compared with England at for\neign trade.\n\"There have been too many American\nbusiness men who have failed In tholr\nown line, who think they can become\nsuccessful exporter. With no study of\nme market they are trying to serve\nabroad, without catering to tha Individ\nlnl or particular wants of the foreign\nbuyer and without keeping themselves\nadequately Informed as to world trade\nconditions, they are Interested chiefly\nIn the 'flint shipment' which often may\nprove the lsst under such circumstances.\nConsequently such exporters are doing\nour foreign trade Incalculable harm, for\nforeign buyers will not put up with,\nsuch dealings longer than necessary.\nThey will buy elae where.\n\"Another thing, we' cannot continue\nselling abroad In the present voume\nunless we begin to take foods In ex\nchange.\" \"Would you knock holes In our tariff\nwnll?\" Mr. Vanderllp was asked.\n\"Thnt will not be necesaary,\" he an\nswered. \"Person Interested In develop\ning our foreign trade might do well to\nconsider the policy of Brltsh menufae\nturera, who take great pains In pleas\ning foreign customers. In specialising In\ntheir respective wsnts and In fostering\npermanent Imalness relation! through\n'repeat' ordrrs.\n\"Wo have excelled In those Industrie\nwhere moss production can be utilised,\nthus satisfying a large home consump\ntion and disposing of the surplus\nabroad.\"\nMr. Vanderllp held however, that the\nC3En30QE3O\nTkls SMtkins. kmllai\nSkMllaf. Maeir.\nM all r lis un.\nlag\nla eut f Svras miss, mu\nsennas, HLtH eulcklv fcaala th\nshut, muhnsi aeute Mar\ntfm rear erastuh\nOf E3t7ui?fGl\nJo Amlrnmn. d run glut, rhttttuoBg\nQUAKER DAY\nOn package Quaker Oat..1Se\nOn package Pancake Flour 15o\nOn package Puffed Rice ,15o\nOn package Puffed Wheat.. 15o\nAll for 60c\nt package of Quaker Flour\nFREE\nCOMPOUND LARD\nBulk, lb 20c\n4-1 b. pall 85c\n8-1 b. pall $1.70\nPAYS TO PAY CASH AT A\nCASH STORE\nTli3S4 Red Stores\n\"Where They Sell For Le\"\nLQWMY\nHAIR\naArWTj\nOf court yotl want Rood looking hair.\nS Your hair wtllb most admired if you use ji\nNelson s Hair Dressing\nKtUM S kit keea tk. ttnoitt kali m\nit\ntins ens ptn\nCM sccrl tt ttn.\nAH tood n tt..tt C\nIn U I. Irrp Nci-\nOIL Boftl'SWf't\ntrsulsf NcIkmi t.\nJ\nlid tftr. T., V\nmm Wi\")1\" t\nit\nfcisisfttsr i\ng;ss ,!!l sukrePoeo'ronaaii1 I\nXL5C.\"i fi'SG. C3 TJcliword, Va.'\nwCX\nK.i \"m-iiairiii wilirllYl\nchier reasons today why American for'\neign iriiuo was lulling on were me\nuuropu a Initial hunger for America\nproducts, due to their war price re\nruperatlon work hers been partly satis.\nfled and that many European nation\nhave exhausted their credit here.\nDiscussing the presidential campaign\nMr. Vanderllp confessed he was sur\nprised and disappointed tkat neither\nthe republican nor democratic party nan\nrisen to tne opportunity Deiore 11.\n\"There was a lamentable lack of out\ntending statesmanship or national lead'\nerahlp shown at the Chicago and Ban\nFrancisco conventions,\" aula Mr. van-\nderllu. \"And I say this as a republican,\n\"As to the presidency Itself, I have\none though upon that. Since Boose\nvolt was president, there ha grown up\nan exagj,'oraica idea of me power ana\nInfluence our chief executive should ex\nercise. I believe our president should\nnot possess powers of a dictator or\nmonarch, i he pos tlon Is an executive\none, designed to carry out the expressed\nwishes of the majority of our people\nand not to furthe r the Ideas, alms or\nambitions of one clique or of one man.\nOBITUARY\nCsot. Frank B. Clay.\nMarietta, Ha., Aug. 25. Burial of\nCapt. Frank B. Clay, ion of the late\nUnited mate Senator Clay, of Geor\ngia, who died Monday at aWlter Kuld\nhospital, Washington, took place here\ntoaay. capt. Clay was a West To lit\ngraduate and 12 year old.\nS. P., McDonel at Rest.\n8, P. McDonel, who died Monday at\nhi homo, 128 East Terrace, was laid\nto rest In forest Hills cemetery, fol\nlowing funeral services from ht. Paul's\nEpiscopal church Wednesday afternoon\nat l:3i) o'clock, Key. Lawrence Fatl-\ncett officiated. Pallbearers were John\nIt. Evnns, L. U. Browne, William Shan\nnon, William Fryar, Mr. 1'hlfer and\nL. raticett.\nira F. Younp at Rest,\nIra F. Young, highly renuected citi\nzen and Confederate veteran, who died\nat his home In Wauhatchle, was laid\nto rest in the Confederate cemetery\nhere following funeral services In Union\nchapel at Wauhatchle Wednesday\nmorning. Kev. K, K. Lewis officiated.\nTha funeral waa largely attended, and\nthere were many beautiful floral offer\nings. Services at tha grave were In\ncharge of the veterans.\nCalvin Edgar Fine,\nThe funeral of Calvin Edgar Fine.\nwho died Tuesday at hi horn near\nValdeau. wllf be held from Union Bethul\nchurch at VaJdeau Thursday morning\nat iv o ciock. The interment will fol\nlow In Greenwood cemetery, with ser\nvices at the grave being In charge of\ntha Masomo lodge, Mr. Fine was a\nmemner oi Mm uity longo Jo, bus.\nand A. M. Pallbearers are an\nnounced as Ernest Bolt, E. G. Cherry,\nB. M. Ward, N. P. Bush, George Been,\nDave Evans, J. H. Lamb, 8. O. Carney,\nI. V. Elder, C. C. Bparkman, C. W.\nNatzger and C. A. Conner.\nClarence c. Benjamin.\nThe funeral of Clarence C. Benjamin.\nwho died Monday night In a local hos\npital, win be neid rrom Chapman\nchattel Thursday morning at id o'clock.\nwith Kev. Hamlo officiating. The In\nterment will lake place In Forest Hill\ncemetery.\nionn Frassr.\nHuntsvllle, Ala.. Aug. 25 (Special.)\nJohn Eraser, one of he pioneer fruit\nnurserymen of the south, and for many\nyears head of the Eraser Nursery com\npany, died last night after a long III-\nicss witn complications, agea vs. fie is\nurvlved by his widow and several sons\nnd daughters, among them being Mrs,\nK. L. Leathorwood, Mra. Robert Har\nrison. James and John Eraser of Hunts\nvllle and W. O.. Eraser of Birmingham.\nFuneral ef Mrs. Norman,\nThe funeral of Mrs. fiallle Massey\nNorman, who died Tuesday morning\nat her home in Bnynton, ua., was nam\nfrom the Boynton M. E. church Wednes\nday afternoon at 2 o'clock, with Kev.\nSmith, the pastor, assisted by Revs.\nW. V. Dalley, J. R. MeFarland and T.\nJ. Houta, officiating. The funeral was\nlargely attended.\nFuneral of Mr. Powell.\nMrs. Luclnda Powell, who died at\nher home on Long street, was lnld to\nrest In Forest Hills cemetery, following\nfuneral services Wednesday afternoon.\nItev. W. M. Tldwell officiated.\nGREENWOOD CEMETERY\nSUGAR MARKET 