the esti\nmates of the aiithorlltes there will be\nno abundance of peaches, apples and\nother fruits In manv sections'. Tt ts re-\nvortcd that there will be a scarcity of\nImrrcls. o that tt will he Imnractlcahle\nto enrry the surnlus In cold storage,\nManifestly, therefore, unless tha m-od-ucls\nare '\"put up\" there will a heavy\nwaste.\nWashington, Aug. 14. -With the\nfurepil release of suiter stocks through\nlightened bank credit, department of\ntnit'ce officials lodnv foreca\"' a further\ntumble In amr prices. There were\nIndlenllona. nnVlnts snld. thnt the un\nloading of stored stocks might rlut the\nmarket and bring a \"subslsnttal drop\"\nIn eddltlon to the present decline.\nThe department has received an\ncla from mint dealers who seek re\nI'rf from the dro'n which already hea\nIntien piece. The ettornev-snernl.\nhowever, will follow a hands-off ttoiicv.\nIt waa staled todev bv his aa!ate\"t.\nt'ohort T, Scott, The department, Ve\np-ot tnM, Is concerned ontv with\nuronteerlng and IndlvMi\"! trsns.ic\nIons ere elv.'n no cons'd-',,on un-ti\"-lil1n'i\nf't ere ph -n.\nLOOKS TO FARMER\nhnt tif hm rTMhrd mnr nttrrdt\nInr Hr-vlr )frtnt of the niit mnn-\nrnjlut hnn hfcfymt 1Mrftrt In trnrV\nIn fttv flu to t lnbrr pffunllon r\nnn In'Hrfttlnn ftt fiturl trrnrt rt\nw-rt In-irnt umnt? rrlH irt! fr\nntil'itntion of nutrtmot lv ffifl-r n J'f:\nfrt-it .i df()-rnitnc, tn M nr'nfon of 1..\nV M'ttll-imft, .1r., urmldrnt of th O.Tr\n\"ft Mntor 1 ru romuny, of leiwn,\nI \"'i in.\nGALVrsTON. Tes. F. T. Fennig.\nsr.nl ..f Hip Msilorv line. In a stale\nno 1 t mi. I thai iMe conditions on\nehli h eiil:ii,g Ion- sh-ri'ipon could re\nturn to li I., 11 itini to them\nor. Aug. I'to e i'ri.!fns Mote\nthtf m-'H n' nti.l.rd nn an\no', n ehoo h: ,1 Co r rs 1,11 Aj.o't\nini\"h! t'me en'\nf.r\n1 b- in n oinn\nTHE CHATTANOOGA NEWS, CHATTANOOGA,\nNEVER SUGAR SHORTAGE,\nr FEDERAL FIGURES SHOW\nStockg in America Are Larger\nThan Ever Before Known,\nIt Is Declared.'\nWashington, Aug. 25 Th \"short\nage\" which created a recant panlo In\nthe sugar market and which aent prices\nsky rocketing, Is now officially disclosed\nto have been a figment -of the Imagi\nnation If It were not designed for the\npurpose of Increased profits. Tho short\nago nover really exiated. On the con\ntrary, while housewives ani others\nwere doing without sugar completely\nor paying exorbitant prices, the sugar\nstocks on hand In the United Riutes\nwere larger by 17 per cent than at any\nni,,f, iii mc mm imea years.\nThese facts were mads nnhtln u the\ndnpartment of crop estimates of the do-\nlartment or agriculture today. Belief\na expressed bv the -bureau .,,,r\nsoon would be retallod at 15 cent per\n)i'!iiv vi lunuii\nThe bureau states that IiiH. th.\nsupposed shortage the amount of sugnr\nIn the United Htntcs waa 1,300,00(1,(100\nI'Mumm mure man ordinary. To have\nused this surplus would have required\nthe Consumntion hv everv mnn ttman\nmm cniid in tne united Btatcs of 103\npound.\nThe following figures ehonr the\namount of sugar on hand for the year\nending June 80.\nDomestic, 1,097.000.000 pounds; Ha-\nwminii, i.ii mi. i i. it i nonmiH' rnh, mA\nother foreign, 7.587.000.000 nnunrls-\nl'ortn Rico. g.'IS.OOO.OOO. Totnl 11 i7i\n000,000. Re-exported, 1,444,000.000. To-\nmi ;ir unnea mates, 9,734,000,000\npounds.\nThe average annual arnel iamIh.\nIa thm ff u 0 \"'\"a\n...j, ir me inr. mree years,\nAntu S A')m AAA AAA\nn u liuunna,\nTIlO bureau lavs tha hlnma tnm th.\ntalk of a shortage at the door of a\npsychological state of mind, The ptib\nlio, It would appear, took the word of\nformer Food Administrator Herbert\nHoover, who was warning the world of\nmimian ann mat or Atty.-Oen.\nPalmer. who threstenel rnn.\nfor any one who attempted to profit\nby it.\nAt th ame time soft drink menu\nfanturers, candy manufacturer and\nother large Users of sugar were stricken\nwith panlo over the artificial situation\nthus created and began to hoard stocks.\nThe bureau points out further that\nthe high price level brotifiht large sugar\nmocks scurryl ig to the United Btates\nfrom every section of the globe.\nIYAR ON PROFITEERING\nIN COAL BROADENED\nDepartment Officials Will Ask\n\"Limit of Law\" Against\nPersons Convicted.\nWashington. Aug. JR A nnounee\nment that the campaign against prof\niteering On Coal Would he hrnndened\nwith especial attention to the situation\nat tldowater points was made' today at\nthe department of Justice,\nThe drive will center at the hnnl.r.\nIng stations of Hampton Roads and\nBaltimore, from which comnlalnt have\nbeen the moat frenuent. \"Renewed an.\ntlvlty\" was ordered at Baltimore yes\nterday, according to Rpeclal Assistant\nAttorney-General Mitchell, who la dl-j\nreeling the campaign against coal prof-'\nIteers.\nThe announcement followed nnbltea.\ntlon hv the federal trade commission\nof findings on an Investigation ehow-\nng that West Virgin a cob coat ng\nIR.40 a ton delivered at Hamnton Roads.\nwa being aold at prlcea ranging as\nnign a szn a ton, Mr. Mttcneu aaid,\nowever, that he had not seen the\ncommission's report and that the de\npartment's announcement waa a second\nstep In the program Indicated when In\nstruction were sent to all United States\ndistrict attorneya Monday ordering\nthem to watch cloaely for enhanced\nprices as a result of pyramiding coal\nQuotations thrsuah resales.\nDepartment cfflclala Indicated their\nIntention of salting \"the limit of the\nlaw\" as a penalty where convictions of\ncoal profiteering are obtained. They\ndeclared they expected to uncover some\nflagrant violations or the Iever act in\nthe t dewater Investigations.\nThe concentration on tidewater ports\nshould not he accepted aa meaning\nthat the prosecution of coal profiteers\nwould be slackened In other part of\ntne country, tt was said. Tne broad\nened Investigation will mean a more\nrigorous Invoatlgatlon In all sections,\nbut for tha nresent the dennrtment's\nattention Is to be directed principally\nat the bunkering porta, It was added,\nOLD LEGEND RELATING\nTO FROG MOUNTAIN\nKimsey Highway Opens up\nHistoric Seotion of Polk\nCounty.\n(BY JOHN 0. tHAMBLIN.)\nBenton, Aug. 23. With the opening\nof the Klmaey highway acroa Little\nFrog mountain It la getting to he one\nof the moat talked-of mountains In\nPolk county, and perhaps In th south.\nJust why these mountains were called\nthe Frog mountalna we have no au\nthentic renord, hut there la more than\none legend. One Is that an Indian\nchief, \"Hlg Frog,\" waa ruler In th\nmountains south of the Ocoe river,\nand his eon, \"I.lltl Frog.\" ruled In\nthe mountalna north of the Ocoee river.\nAnother la tha mountain was so\nnamed on account of so msny frogs\nbeing found on flicm. And snnther Is\nthat th word fog waa tnlsused by the\nearly settlers and In that way the\nmountain got to hi called Frog moun\ntain. C. P. Williams, who surveyed\ntha Klmaev highway, has the Idea\nthat the nlglnnl name was fog In place\nof frog. In a letter to the writer he\nsave of thla: \"It appears that the name\nof the mountains Is- not really a name\nnor a nameaake. it wouin men re\nmain for It to h a nickname and,\naccording to, our best Information, a\nnlrknsm it la. for these mountains\nwere first called the \"Fog\" mountains,\nand no other name could he more fit\nting. For there Is not a flay in tne\nveer when the air la humid that at\nsome time between the rising and set\nting of the sun the mists do siot gather\nand hang around their lony sum\nmits.\nThe Indlnn word wninaj means iron,\nand In Monnev'a \"Mvtha of. the Chero-\nkees.\" page 2St. we find th following:\n\"The animals or tne neroare invuu,\nIlk the traditional hern-gods, were\nlarger and of more perrect ivpe mnn\ntheir present representatives. They\nhad chiefs councils and towntiouses.\ntnlnelcd with human kind upon irrnis\nof perfect equality and spoke the same\nlanruase.\n\"Ksch animal had his appointed sta\ntion and duty. Thus tho walnsl (fmt\nwaa the marshal and leader in \"'r\ncouncil, while 