nthe home of Jefferson Pavla. the only\npresident of the Confcdeate Statea of\nAmerica. In this city. Gov. Thomaa E.\nKilhy announced that he was ready at\nany moment to aii;n a warrant for !5,\nnon appropriated by the legislature of\nfor tniri-haee and removal of the\nared build ng.\nCOTTON SELLS OFF IN\nEARLY MARKET HOURS\nNew York, Aug. 25. Yesterday' re\ncovery wa followed by repewed weak\nness fa th cotton market today, Liv,\nrpool cable made a favorable ahow\nIng. but no Improvement wa reported\nIn the good trade, th feather In th\nsoutn wa oeiier, jtna a private crop re\nport making the condition 70.9 per\ncent, compared wth 75.3 per cent, a\nmonth ago, placed the crop indication\nat 13,400,000 balea, or 900,000 bale above\nthe orricial end-juiy i gyres. The open\ning was barely steady at unchanged\nprices to a decline of 15 points, and\nafter the execution of overnight bovine\norders, the market sold off to 26.68c\nfor October ana ia.vso tor December,\nor about 60 to 60 points below last\nnight's closing. The weakness of New\nOrleans was a factor on the decline here\nand there was a good deal of southern\nselling,\nAfter showing net losses of 87 to 88\npoints, the market rallied slightly be\nfore the publication 'of the weekly re\nport of the weather bureau and there\nwas a little covering on tne report It\nself, which read rather unfavorably.\nDemand fulled to broaden, however, and\na bulge of some 15 to 30 point met re\nnewed pressure, witn price making\nnew low for the day early In the noon\nhour.1 October sold off to 26.40a and\nDecember to 26.00, or 90 to 100 points\nbelow lust night's closing. Local trad\ners reported steady southern selling here\nand a continued alack of demand for\nearly new crop shipment in the south\nwest.\nTh early afternoon break carried De\ncomber off to 24.80c with active months\ngiuierully showing; net losses ef 106 to\n136 points, but Inter December rallied to\n25.57c on bullish private crop report\nIrom Texas and covering.\nNEW ORLEANS 6POT COTTON\nNew Orleans, Aug, 25 Spot cotton\naulct and unchanged: sale on the snot.\n120 bodies; to arrive, none; low middling.\n20. toe; middling, ai.otic; good middling,\n34.75c; receipts. Dales; stock, 206,-\n649 bales.\nNEW ORLEANS COTTON\nNew Orleahs, Aug. 25. A weak mar\nket prevailed In cotton during the first\nhour of business today and active\nmonth dropped to level 96 to 103\npoints under the close of yesterday.\nOctober went as low a 25.30c and\nMarch a low as 23.86c. Poor cables,\nfairly good weather over the belt and\nprivate bureau Indicated crop figures of\nover ia.uuo.ooo caies were responsible\n(or tne aeiung,\nThe weekly cotton crop reports were\nconsidered more favorable than ex\npected, the heaviest kind of selling fol\nlowed their reading to the ring, and it\nwas not. well absorbed. Late in the\nmorning the trading months were 130 to\n141 points under the close of yesterday.\nOctober went as low a 24.95c and\nMarch to 23.50c.\nIn the late trading extremely heavy\nrealizing of profit by shorts wa done\nand it created a good demand which\nwa not any too well supplied, the re\nsult being that toward the close prices\nwere 60 to 70 points up from the low\nest of the session.\nLIVERPOOL COTTON.\nLiverpool, Aug, 25. Cotton spot dull;\nprices irregular; good middling, 25.33d:\nfully middling, 23.83d; middling, 22.58d;\nlow middling, 18.78d; good ordinary,\n15.33d; ordinary, 14.33d; sales, 3,000\nbales, Including 2,600 American; re\nceipts, 10,000 bales, Including 2,000\nAmerican; futures closed weak and Ir\nregular: August, 20.10d; October,\n19.26d: January, 18.46d; March, 18.14d;\nMay, 17.74d; July, 17.39d.\nNEW ORLEANS COTTON FUTURES\nOPENING.\nNew Orleans, Aug. 26. Cotton futures\noponed steady: October, 26.2026.21c;\nDecember, 25.24c; January, 24.87c;\nMarch, 24.68c\" bid; May, 24.38c.\nNEW ORLEANS COTTON FUTURES\nCLOSING.\nNew Orleans, Aug. 25 Cotton futures\nclosed very steady at net declines of\n42 to 60 points: October. 26.30c; De\ncember, 24.87c: January, 24.50c; March,\n24.20c; May, 23.90c.\nNEW YORK COTTON FUTURES\nOPENING.\nNew York, wug. 25. Cotton futures\nopened barely steady: October, 27.4c;\nDcoembcr, 26.10c; January, 25.38c;\nMarch, 25.00c; May, 24.70c.\nNEW YORK COTTON FUTURES\nCLOSING.\nNew York, Aug. 25 Cotton future\nclosed teady; October, 27.05c; Decem\nber, 26.68c; January. 24.90c: March.\n24.70o; May, 24.65c.\nt\nMATTERS OF RECORD\nReal Estate Transfers.\nW. O. Wade to S. M Keith, land In\nSecond district; $700.\n8. J. A. Frailer and wife to Thomas\nCowart, land In Third district; $750.\nN. T. Montague to J. A. Neal, land In\nSecond district; $450.\nW. S. Shelton and wife to T. F. Shel\nton and wife, land in Second district;\n$1,750.\nKntherlne Ault to Margaret Aull, land\nin Eleventh ward; $360.\nJ. H. Italns and wife to James K.\nOang and wife, land In Second district;\n$2,250.\nA, Mitchell to L. A. Price and wife.\nland In Second dlatrlct; $1,625.\nJ. A. Neal and wife to M. E. Brown\nand wife, land in Second district;\n$1,200.\nA. D. Langlola to Mra. Ruth Dawson,\nland In First district; $3,250.\nAlbert W. House and wife to W. L.\nBrown, land In Second dlatrlct; $900.\nClyde M. linger and husband to G.\nA. Anderson.' land in Second district;\n$2,050.\nH. F. Bradahaw to Jennie Spigener,\nland In Second district; $1B0.\nHorace V. Scott and wife to G. H.\nKlemm, land In First district; $3,600.\nZ. C. Patten to city of Chattanooga\nand Hamilton county, land in Hamil\nton .county; $25,000.\nKva C. Kmhry to C Z. Taylor and\nwife. land In Second district; $2,060.\nHaas M. Provence and husband to\nLouis H. Bull, land In Second dlatrlct;\n$7,000.\nLouis H. Bull and wife to Bess M.\nProvence, land In Second district; $500\nSam Erwln. clerk and master, to U,\nT. Thomas, Jland in Second district;\n$616.\nMaynard Levatt to H. s. Norton, lana\nIn Second district; 2U0.\nThomaa Crutchfte d to c. w. Tyier,\nland In Second district; $3,000.\nC. W. Tv er to Thomaa Crutcnneid,\nland In Secon