1; low\nest last night, 69; mean, 70; wet bulb.\nI p.m,,'t3: wet bulD, 7 a.m., 68.\nCorresponding dote last yeaf (de\ngrees) Highest, 8; lowest, 68; mean,\n77. I\nNormal for this date, 75 degree.\nAccumulated deficiency In tempera\nture since Jan. 1, 345 degrees.\nRelative humidity (per cent.) T p.m.,\n61: 7 a.m.. 80,\nPrecipitation for twenty-four hour\nending 7 a.m. today, .0 inch.\nTotal precipitation since Jana. 1, 56.02\ninches.\nAccumulated excess Is 20.21 Int-hes,\nHighest wind velocity for twenty-four\nhours ending 7 a.m. today, 12 miles\nnorthwest.\nRiver stage at 7 a.m. (feet), 16. S;\nfall In twenty-four hours (feet). 0.8.\nWeather for Four State.\nWashington, Aug. 25. Forecast\nKentucky. Tennessee Fair tonight\nand Thursday; not .much change In\ntemperature.\nGeorgia Fair tonight and Thursday;\nslightly cooler in south portloa tonight.\nAlabama Fair tonight and Thuradav:\n.moderate temperature.\nutin 1234561234566\nLuella Black.\nLuella Black. 13-year-old daughter of\nMrs. Joe R. Black, formerly of this\ncity, but now of Wartrace, died last\nFriday morning at St. Thomas hospital\nIn Nashville following an operation for\nappendicitis. hhad been sick only a\nfew days.\nLuella attended the Rldgedalo and\nRossville schools and made a host of\nfriends while here. She was a member\npt the Methodist church, was a regular\nniimiuttiii. in wie jMiinmy acnooi ana an\nactive worker In both the Junior and\nSenior leagues. She Is survived by herT\nmother, two slaters, Mary Oillveene and\nJosephine Istfm, and a number of rela\ntives. Funeral services were held last Sat\nurday at the Methodist church In War\ntrace, with Dr. Hill, the paator, offici\nating. The Interment took place in\nYates cemetery.\nThe Five-Pointed Star.\n1 The ancient Greeks used the five\npointed star as a symbol of health. 1\nstill fulfills this ancient mission, as you\nwill find It Imprinted on each package\nof Chamberlain's Tablets. These tab\nlets have restored hundreds to healaii\nwho were af